\section{Čech cohomology of the structure sheaf (iter-012 scaffold)}
\label{sec:moduleK_cech}

This section opens \emph{Path-2} of Phase~A step~6: the Čech-cohomology approach to Serre finiteness for $H^i(C, \struct C)$ on a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve. Iter-012 lays the smallest useful sub-step: define the Čech complex of $\toModuleKSheaf C$ for an arbitrary indexed open cover, plus its cohomology object in each degree. Iter-013+ will add the comparison theorem (Čech vs derived-functor cohomology, for an acyclic cover), the affine-finiteness step (each cochain group is a finite-dimensional $k$-vector space when the cover is affine), and the dimension-vanishing step (degree $> 1$ vanishes on a curve); together they will produce the Serre-finiteness instance \lstinline{Module.Finite k (HModule k (toModuleKSheaf C) i)} that downstream \lstinline{smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus} consumes.

The carrier on which the iter-013+ work will operate is the Mathlib functor \lstinline{CategoryTheory.cechComplexFunctor} (\texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Cech.lean}): given a presheaf $F : \Cop \to A$ on a category $C$ with finite products, valued in a preadditive category $A$ with products, and an indexed family $\mathcal U : \iota \to C$, this returns a cochain complex
\[
  \check C^\bullet(\mathcal U; F) \;:=\; (\mathtt{cechComplexFunctor}\,\mathcal U).\mathrm{obj}\,F \;\in\; \mathtt{CochainComplex}(A, \mathbb N).
\]
For $A = \ModuleCat\,k$, $C = \opens(C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat})$ (a complete lattice, hence a category with finite products via meets), and $F = (\mathtt{sheafToPresheaf}\,\_\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\toModuleKSheaf C)$ the underlying presheaf of the iter-006 structure sheaf, the Čech complex is well-defined; its $n$-th cohomology lives in $\ModuleCat\,k$.

\begin{definition}[Čech complex of the structure sheaf]
  \label{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cechCochain_OC}
  \uses{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Let $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$ and $\mathcal U : \iota \to \opens C.\mathrm{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$ be an indexed family of opens. Define
  \[
    \mathtt{cechCochain\_OC}\,(C)(\mathcal U) \;:=\; (\mathtt{cechComplexFunctor}\,\mathcal U).\mathrm{obj}\,\bigl((\mathtt{sheafToPresheaf}\,\_\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\toModuleKSheaf C)\bigr).
  \]
  This is a cochain complex valued in $\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k$, indexed by $\mathbb N$.
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  Direct application of Mathlib's \lstinline{cechComplexFunctor}. The required typeclasses (\lstinline{HasProducts (ModuleCat.{u} k)}, \lstinline{HasFiniteProducts (Opens C.left.toTopCat)}, \lstinline{Preadditive (ModuleCat.{u} k)}) are all auto-resolved. The closure body is therefore the one-line term \lstinline{(cechComplexFunctor 𝒰).obj ((sheafToPresheaf _ _).obj (Scheme.toModuleKSheaf C))}; iter-012 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe confirms this typechecks end-to-end against current Mathlib + project state.
\end{proof}

\begin{definition}[Čech cohomology of the structure sheaf]
  \label{def:Scheme_cechCohomology_OC}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.cechCohomology_OC}
  \uses{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}
  With $(C, \mathcal U)$ as in Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}, define for each $n : \mathbb N$
  \[
    \mathtt{cechCohomology\_OC}\,(C)(\mathcal U)(n) \;:=\; \bigl(\mathtt{cechCochain\_OC}\,(C)(\mathcal U)\bigr).\mathtt{homology}\,n \;\in\; \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k.
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}
  Direct application of \lstinline{HomologicalComplex.homology} on the cochain complex of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_cechCochain_OC}. The closure body is the one-line term \lstinline{(Scheme.cechCochain_OC C 𝒰).homology n}.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[What iter-012 does and does not do]
  Iter-012 \emph{defines} the Čech cochain complex and Čech cohomology object of the structure sheaf for an arbitrary indexed open cover. Iter-012 does \emph{not} prove that this Čech cohomology agrees with the derived-functor cohomology $\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf C)\,n$ of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} — the comparison theorem requires the cover to be \emph{acyclic} (e.g., all opens affine, plus Serre's vanishing on affine schemes for quasi-coherent sheaves), neither of which is iter-012 work. The comparison theorem is queued for iter-013+; the affine-finiteness step (each cochain group is finite-dimensional over $k$ when the cover is affine and the curve is proper) is queued for iter-014+; the dimension-vanishing step (degree $> 1$ vanishes on a curve) is queued for iter-015+.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Why two declarations and not one]
  Splitting $\check C^\bullet$ from $\check H^n$ matches Mathlib's standard pattern (\lstinline{cechComplexFunctor} returns a complex; \lstinline{HomologicalComplex.homology} extracts a degree). The complex is useful in its own right (e.g., for explicit cocycle / coboundary calculations, or for showing exactness on a specific cover), so we expose it as a separate API surface.
\end{remark}

